^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|Bonus for very experienced players:

ALERT:  What does it mean if you jump overcall after they have preempted?  For example in:|
ht|e|cs|6|
at|^B{|ia|,,2h3s|at|}|
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


ht|g|at|^jauction, or.|
ht|h|cs|6|at|^B{|ia|,,2h4c|at|}|ht|i|at|^jthis auction you are South with 3@S and 4@C bids.|
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


ht|k|AT|^B@2There is a good saying: "You can't preempt a preempt." Once your opponent has preempted, you shouldn't also be able to preempt. Therefore, the jumps in the auctions above don't show weak hands. They show good hands. How good? "Intermediate." |
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


AT|

This means about 16-18 in playing strength (more than a full opening bid) and a good 6+ card suit. So, on the first example, a 3@S jump overcall would look something like:

|ih|pSKQJ1097HA2DKQJC32|at| or |ih|pSAQJ9872H2DAQ3C76.|
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


nt||
%%%
qx||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|In the second auction,|ht|c|cs|6|at|^B{|ia|,,2h4c|at|}|ht|c|at|^j@2without any special agreements, the jump to 4@C would also show an intermediate hand with 6+ good clubs.|
ht|f|at|^b@2However, many experts use this jump (to 4-of-a-minor) as a Roman Jump Overcall |CP|1|AT|^*Hwww.larryco.com/bridge-learning-center/detail/116^*N|CP||AT|. You would need to discuss with your partner if you use this method. If so, a jump to 4@C shows 5+C and 5+ in the other major. A jump to 4@D is 5+D and 5+ of the other major. So, in the auction shown above, 4@C would be 5+C and 5+S.|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


AT|

When using Roman Jump Overcalls, the cuebid (3@H) in the auction above is freed up to ask for a stopper. It won't be Michaels |CP|1|AT|^*Hwww.larryco.com/bridge-learning-center/detail/761^*N|CP||AT| (since the Roman Jump covers the 5-5 hand). The cuebid would show a good hand (usually with a running suit) and requests partner to bid 3NT with their suit stopped.|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


AT| 

Summary of jumps after their preempts: All such jumps show GOOD hands. Make sure you and your partner know if you are using Roman Jump Overcalls to 4-of-a-minor.|
pg| ***** 25 ***** |


AT|

^B@2^*BMM: What Cohen calls "Roman Jump Overcalls" is also known as "Leaping Michaels" (which Howard finds more descriptive name since it shows a Michaels type 5-5 hand). Howard thinks that Leaping Michaels is a better way to play a jump to 4@C or 4@D than having it show a single suited minor hand. As Cohen suggests, this lets you play a 3-level cue bid over a weak 2 as asking for a stopper. That comes up fairly frequently and lets you get to 3NT when appropriate. The 3@H/3@S cue bid as stopper ask only applies over 2@H and 2@S openers. A 3@D cue bid over 2@D is still Michaels.|
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


AT|

As with any conventions, especially lesser known ones like those mentioned in the previous paragraph, please make sure you and your partner are in full agreement and will not forget what they mean. If there is any danger that one of you will forget, then you should revert to having jumps to 4@C and 4@D being natural and cue bids of 3@H and 3@S as Michaels.^*N|
